item.description:
Prove that <span class="math">\cos 3\th = 4\cos^3\th - 3\cos \th</span>, and use it to solve the cubic equation <div class="math"> 24x^3 - 72x^2 +66x -19 = 0. </div><h3> Solution</h3>In general, let us start with a monic cubic <span class="math">x^3+\al x^2 + \be x + \ga = 0.</span> We can eliminate the quadratic term by translation <span class="math">y = x-a</span>: <br><div class="math"> 0 = y^3 + y^2 (\al-3a) + y(3a^2-2a\al + \be) + \hat\ga, </div> so choosing <span class="math">\al = 3a</span> we reduce the cubic to <div class="math"> y^3 - \frac{D}{12}y  + \hat\ga = 0.</div>Note that the condition for the cubic to have a critical point <span class="math">3x^2+2\al x + \be = 0</span> is <span class="math">D=4(\al^2-3\be)\geq0</span>. <br>If <span class="math">D&gt;0</span>, we can rescale <span class="math">z=\frac{\sqrt{D}}{3}y</span> to obtain <div class="math"> \frac{D^{3/2}}{4\times3^3} (4z^3 - 3z +k ) =0 </div>In our example, <span class="math">\al=3a=-3,\be=\frac{33}{12}, D=3</span>, so that <span class="math">-k=\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}</span>, so that the solutions are <div class="math"> 
x = 1 + \frac{\cos\al\frac{\pi}{18}}{\sqrt{3}}
</div> where <span class="math">\al\in\{1,11,13\}</span>
